lled Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Cynan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Dinan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dinan","meanings":["Irish (now mainly counties Clare and Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Daghnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Daghnán</i>’, possibly a diminutive of <i>dagh</i> ‘good’.","Irish: variant of   Dineen  .","French: habitational name from Dinan, in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gruffudd ap Cynan was born in 1065, in Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cynan ap Lago, was 25 and his mother, Ragnalt Olafdotter Ingen Amlaib, was 25. He married Eva Arddyu in 1090, in Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1065–":"1065–Surnud","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1081–1137":"1081–1137","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1040–Female":"1040–Surnud","1090":"1090","1137":"1137","1065":"1065","1040":"1040","1081":"1081","Llandilo, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Llandilo, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Monmouth Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Dublin or MONMOUTH Wales":"Dublin, Iirimaa","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1065–":"1065–Kuollut","1065–Male":"1065–Kuollut","1065–Female":"1065–Kuollut","1081–1137":"1081–1137","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1040–Female":"1040–Kuollut","1090":"1090","1137":"1137","1065":"1065","1040":"1040","1081":"1081","Llandilo, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Llandilo, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Monmouth 